'''Fabián Ruiz Peña''' ({{IPA|es|faˈβjan rwiθ ˈpeɲa}}; born 3 April 1996),<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Ángel Lara |first=Miguel |date=2019-09-05 |title=Fabián Ruiz: "Mi ídolo es mi madre" |trans-title=Fabián Ruiz: "My idol is my mother" |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/seleccion/2019/09/05/5d7012bc22601d7a6e8b4613.html |access-date=2025-05-11 |website=Marca.com |language=es}}</ref> also known simply as '''Fabián''', is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[central midfielder]] for {{French football updater|PSG}} club [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].

==Club career==
===Real Betis===
====Early years====
Born in [[Los Palacios y Villafranca]], [[Province of Seville|Seville]], [[Andalusia]], Fabián joined [[Real Betis]]' youth setup in 2004, aged eight, after starting it out at EF La Unión de Los Palacios.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estadiodeportivo.com/betis/2014/11/20/fabian-sigue-quemando-etapas-rumbo-elite/33052.html|title=Fabián sigue quemando etapas rumbo a la elite|trans-title=Fabián keeps on skipping stages towards the elite|publisher=[[Estadio Deportivo]]|date=20 November 2014|access-date=14 December 2014|language=es}}</ref>

Ruiz has credited his mother with bringing him into football.<ref name=":1" /> He was promoted to [[Real Betis B|the reserves]] in July 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cuentaconlacantera.com/fabian-y-gavi-dos-palaciegos-en-el-futuro-del-betis/|title=Fabián y Gavi, dos palaciegos en el futuro del Betis|trans-title=Fabián and Gavi, two ''Palaciegos'' in Betis' future|publisher=Cuenta con la Cantera|language=es|date=16 September 2014|access-date=14 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023818/http://www.cuentaconlacantera.com/fabian-y-gavi-dos-palaciegos-en-el-futuro-del-betis/|archive-date=9 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and made his senior debut on 21 September, coming on as a second half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 4–1 home loss against [[Marbella FC|Marbella]] in the [[Segunda División B]] championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diariosur.es/deportes/mas-deportes/201409/21/marbella-golea-domicilio-betis-20140921231523.html|title=El Marbella golea a domicilio al Betis B|trans-title=Marbella thrashes Betis B away from home|publisher=Diario Sur|language=es|date=21 September 2014|access-date=17 December 2014}}</ref>

Fabián played his first match as a professional on 16 December, replacing [[Xavi Torres]] in the 51st minute of a 1–0 [[Segunda División]] away win against [[CD Lugo|Lugo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/2014/12/13/futbol/2adivision/1418504932.html|title=El Betis derriba el fortín del Lugo y se acerca a zona de ascenso|trans-title=Betis breaks down Lugo's fortress and draws near the promotion zone|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=13 December 2014|access-date=17 December 2014}}</ref>

Fabián made his debut in the main category of Spanish football on 23 August 2015, coming on as a substitute for [[Alfred N'Diaye]] in a 1–1 home draw against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/la-liga/jornada_1/bet_vil/|title=Rubén Castro llega justo a tiempo|trans-title=Rubén Castro arrives just in time|publisher=Marca|language=es|date=24 August 2015|access-date=1 September 2015}}</ref>

====Loan to Elche====
On 23 December of the following year he renewed his contract until 2019, and was immediately loaned to [[Elche CF|Elche]] in the second level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realbetisbalompie.es/en/noticias/last-news/8243/fabian-se-marcha-cedido-al-elche-cf|title=Fabián extends his contract and goes on loan to Elche CF|publisher=Real Betis|date=23 December 2016|access-date=25 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805015502/http://realbetisbalompie.es/en/noticias/last-news/8243/fabian-se-marcha-cedido-al-elche-cf|archive-date=5 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

====Breakthrough====
Upon returning, Fabián became a regular starter under new manager [[Quique Setién]], scoring his first goal in the top tier on 25 September 2017 in a 4–0 home routing of [[Levante UD|Levante]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2022}} The following 31 January, he renewed his contract until 2023, setting his buyout clause at [[Euro|€]]30 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=El Betis hace oficial la renovación de Fabián Ruiz hasta 2023|trans-title=Betis turn official the renewal of Fabián Ruiz until 2023|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/betis/2018/01/31/5a722db4e2704e6b408b466a.html|website=Marca|language=es|date=31 January 2018|access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref>

On 30 April 2018, Fabián scored the winning goal for Betis as they secured [[UEFA Europa League]] qualification for the [[2018–19 UEFA Europa League|2018–19 season]] following a 2–1 home win over [[Málaga CF|Málaga]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 April 2018 |title=LaLiga - Betis 2-1 Malaga: Betis qualify for the Europa League with win over Malaga |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/04/30/5ae783dc46163f17368b464f.html |access-date=11 May 2025 |website=MARCA in English |language=en}}</ref>

===Napoli===
On 5 July 2018, Fabián joined [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] on a five-year contract until 2023 with Napoli reportedly paying Fabián's €30 million buyout clause.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Napoli Confirm Signing of Real Betis Talent Fabian Ruiz on Long Term Contract |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/07/05/napoli-confirm-signing-real-betis-talent-fabian-ruiz-long-term-contract |magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=5 July 2018 |title=Official: Napoli pay Ruiz clause - Football Italia |url=https://football-italia.net/official-napoli-pay-ruiz-clause/ |access-date=11 May 2025 |website=football-italia.net |language=en-GB}}</ref> He made his debut on 16 September in a Champions League group game away to [[Red Star Belgrade]], playing the full 90 minutes of a goalless draw.<ref>{{cite news |title=Le formazioni ufficiali di Stella Rossa-Napoli: Milik titolare, debutta Fabian Ruiz |trans-title=Official line-ups for Red Star-Napoli: Milik starter, Fabián Ruiz debuts|url=https://it.eurosport.com/calcio/champions-league/2018-2019/le-formazioni-ufficiali-di-stella-rossa-napoli-milik-titolare-debutta-fabian-ruiz_sto6937627/story.shtml |access-date=17 May 2019 |publisher=Eurosport |date=18 September 2018 |language=it}}</ref> Ten days later he played his first [[Serie A]] match and first at the [[Stadio San Paolo]], a 3–0 win over [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Fabian Ruiz, l'esordio al San Paolo: prestazione brillante e priva di errori|trans-title=Fabián Ruiz, debut at the San Paolo: brilliant performance and devoid of errors |url=https://www.napolicalciolive.com/2018/09/27/napoli-esordio-fabian-ruiz/|publisher=Napoli Calcio Live|date=27 September 2018|access-date=17 May 2019|language=it}}</ref>

=== Paris Saint-Germain ===
On 30 August 2022, Fabián signed for [[Ligue 1]] club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] (PSG) on a five-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fabián Ruiz signs five-year deal with Paris Saint-Germain |url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/fabian-ruiz-signs-five-year-deal-with-paris-saint-germain-psg-mercato|date=30 August 2022|publisher=[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.]]}}</ref> He made his debut as a substitute in a 1–0 victory over [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]] at the [[Parc des Princes]] on 10 September 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 September 2022 |title=First appearance for Fabian Ruiz |url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/first-appearance-for-fabian-ruiz-psg-ligue-1-players-squad |access-date=10 September 2022 |publisher=[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.]]}}</ref> On 1 February 2023, he scored his first PSG goal in a 3–1 win over [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Losada |first=Antonio |date=2 February 2023 |title=Montpellier 1-3 PSG: Fabian Ruiz assists and scores in costly snoozefest |url=https://psgpost.com/posts/montpellier-1-3-psg-fabian-ruiz-assists-scores-mbappe-injured |access-date=11 May 2025 |website=PSG Post |language=en-us}}</ref> At the end of the season, Fabián won the Ligue 1 title with PSG, his first top-flight league title.<ref name=":0" />

On 7 May 2025, Fabián scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal with a volley from outside the box in the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League semi-final second leg]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], helping Paris Saint-Germain reach the [[2025 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]] to play against [[Inter Milan]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=7 May 2025 |title=Paris 2-1 Arsenal (agg: 3-1): Fabián Ruiz and Achraf Hakimi strike to send hosts to Champions League final |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0299-1db3d8315aed-982bd1c7792e-1000--paris-2-1-arsenal-agg-3-1-fabian-ruiz-and-achraf-hakimi-s/ |access-date=8 May 2025 |website= |publisher=[[UEFA]] |language=en}}</ref> He was a key component in the PSG side that went on to win the Champions League as part of a [[continental treble]], finishing 24th in the [[2025 Ballon d'Or]] rankings.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Athletic |first=The |date=22 September 2025 |title=Ballon d'Or — 24. Fabian Ruiz |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/ballon-dor-2025-live-updates-winners-time-result/26ouotchoNbJ/ |access-date=18 January 2026 |website=The Athletic |language=en-US}}</ref>

[[File:UEFA EURO qualifiers Sweden vs Spain 20191015 Fabian Ruiz 6 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Fabián playing for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in 2019]]

==International career==
After representing Spain at [[Spain national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Spain national under-21 football team|under-21 levels]], Fabián was called up to the [[Spain national football team|Spain senior team]] by manager [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] on 15 March 2019, for two [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] matches against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] and [[Malta national football team|Malta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sefutbol.com/en/official-call-first-two-euro-qualifier-matches|title=OFFICIAL {{!}} Call-up for the first two EURO Qualifier matches|publisher=SeFutbol|date=15 March 2019|access-date=15 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091031/https://www.sefutbol.com/en/official-call-first-two-euro-qualifier-matches|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He debuted on 7 June 2019 in a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group F|UEFA Euro 2020 qualifier]] against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]], coming on as a substitute for [[Isco]] in the 74th minute.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Miguel Ángel|last=Lara|title=2019, el año de los cristales rotos en la historia de la selección|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/seleccion/2019/12/27/5dff963a268e3e8f238b457f.html|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=27 December 2019|language=es|via=Goleada a Suecia, Kepa y relevo confirmado|quote=Ese día debuta con la absoluta el gran impacto de la selección en 2019, Fabián Ruiz.|trans-quote=That day, the great impact of the national team in 2019, Fabián Ruiz, debuts with the senior team.}}</ref> Four days later, he made his full debut, starting alongside [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Dani Parejo]] in midfield against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]], assisting [[Mikel Oyarzabal]]'s goal in the 87th minute of the 3–0 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary/_/gameId/529018|title=Match Commentary - Sweden vs Spain|website=ESPN|access-date=20 June 2024}}</ref> In July 2019, Fabián returned to the Spain U21 squad for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]. In the team's opening match, he assisted [[Dani Ceballos]]'s opening goal for ''La Rojita'' in a 3–1 loss to host nation [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]]. After being an unused substitute in the second match against [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium]], he scored the third goal of the 5–0 win over [[Poland national under-21 football team|Poland]] in the final Group A fixture. During the knockout stage, he assisted [[Dani Olmo]]'s goal in the semi-final against [[France national under-21 football team|France]] and scored the opening goal of the 2–1 win against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship final|the final]], as well as recording his third assist when [[Dani Olmo]] scored the winning goal following up his long-range shot. He was named Player of the Tournament by [[UEFA]] for his performances in Spain's midfield as they won their fifth European U21 title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/025c-0f2d6f3aab14-2d8ed6ef764d-1000--2019-under-21-euro-player-of-the-tournament-fabian-ruiz/|title=2019 Under-21 Euro Player of the Tournament: Fabián Ruiz|website=UEFA|access-date=20 June 2024}}</ref> Fabián scored his first goal for the Spain senior team in their final Euro 2024 qualifier against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] on 18 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50467133|title=Spain 5-0 Romania: Hosts wrap up Euro 2020 qualifying in style|language=English|date=18 November 2019|access-date=20 June 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 24 May 2021, Fabián was included in Luis Enrique's [[UEFA Euro 2020 squads#Spain|24-man squad]] for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Jamie|last=Braidwood|title=Euro 2020 news Live: Sergio Ramos left out of Spain squad plus latest before England announcement|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/euro-2020-news-live-england-squad-b1852654.html|website=[[The Independent]]|date=24 May 2021}}</ref> He made three substitute appearances at the tournament, against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Poland national football team|Poland]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group E|group stage]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/spain-vs-sweden/teams/421490|title=Spain vs Sweden|language=English|date= |access-date=20 June 2024|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/19/spain-v-poland-euro-2020-live|title=Spain v Poland: Euro 2020 – live!|language=English|date=19 June 2021|access-date=20 June 2024|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/euro-2020/2021/euro-2020-croatia-v-spain-follow-live_sto8392131/story.shtml|title=Euro 2020 – Croatia v Spain – Follow LIVE|language=English|date=28 June 2021|access-date=20 June 2024|website=Eurosport}}</ref>

In June 2023, Fabián was part of the Spain squad for the [[2023 UEFA Nations League Finals]] and played 16 minutes as a substitute for [[Mikel Merino]] in the semi-final against [[Italy national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rfef.es/en/noticias/spain-italy-match-report-nations-league|title=Spain 2–1 Italy: Match Report – Nations League|website=RFEF|access-date=20 June 2024}}</ref> On 18 June, he started in the final against Croatia, playing 78 minutes before being substituted for Merino as Spain won 5–4 in the [[penalty shootout]] to win their first [[UEFA Nations League]] title.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spain 0–0 Croatia (19 Jun, 2023) Final Score – ESPN (AU) |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/match/_/gameId/654361/spain-croatia |access-date=11 May 2025 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

In June 2024, Ruiz was named in Spain's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2024 |title=OFFICIAL {{!}} Final Spain squad for the Euro 2024 finals |url=https://rfef.es/en/noticias/final-spain-squad-for-the-euro-2024-finals |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |access-date=20 June 2024 }}</ref> In the team's opening match of the tournament, he scored Spain's second goal as they beat Croatia 3–0 at Berlin's [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympiastadion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cq55l3qe24jt#Line-ups|title=Spain 3–0 Croatia LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=20 June 2024}}</ref> Fabián played as a starter during the rest of the tournament helping Spain win their fourth European championship.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lewis |first=Andy |date=15 July 2024 |title=Yamal, Williams and Fabian shine as Spain dominate Euro 2024 team of the tournament |url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/football/2024/07/15/yamal-williams-and-fabian-shine-as-spain-dominate-euro-2024-team-of-the-tournament/ |access-date=15 July 2024 |website=The National |language=en}}</ref>

==Style of play==
A left-footed [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], Fabián is known for his vision, passing, ball control and dribbling skills, as well as his tactical versatility, and can play in a number of [[formation (association football)|formations]], such as 4–4–2, 4–3–3, and 4–2–3–1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimouomo.com/chi-e-davvero-fabian-ruiz|title=Chi è davvero Fabian Ruiz|trans-title=Who really is Fabian Ruiz|website=ultimouomo.com|publisher=L'Ultimo Uomo|date=22 June 2018|access-date=2 April 2020|language=it}}</ref> He can also play as a [[defensive midfielder]] or an [[attacking midfielder]].

